WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.960
[Music]

00:00:05.960 --> 00:00:11.480
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. In this&nbsp;
series on foundational issues in mathematics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.480 --> 00:00:18.560
we've been talking about algebra. Algebra is a&nbsp;
large subject characterized by the use of letters&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:18.560 --> 00:00:26.840
to often represent numbers, and we've talked about&nbsp;
the usage of letters in equations as representing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:26.840 --> 00:00:35.000
unknown numbers. Today, we're going to look&nbsp;
at a different role for letters in algebra by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:41.520
first of all having a look at some interesting&nbsp;
patterns formed from geometrical sequences.

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:46.880
Here are the squares. These are actually&nbsp;
literally geometrical squares, and we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.880 --> 00:00:56.840
counting the areas of these squares: 1² =&nbsp;
1, 2² = 4, 3² = 9, and so on. These numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:56.840 --> 00:01:02.120
are important numbers in mathematics; they're&nbsp;
called the squares, and we can represent them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.120 --> 00:01:14.680
algebraically by the use of the term n². So the&nbsp;
nth square is n², which I remind you means n * n.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:23.760
Here the letter n is representing a natural&nbsp;
number, in other words, 1, 2, 3, 4, and so on.

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:31.120
Here's another famous family of special numbers:&nbsp;
the triangular numbers. Let's give them a name;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:38.760
let's call the nth triangular number T_n.&nbsp;
Geometrically, how they arise is by stacking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:47.720
up some balls in a triangular kind of pyramid:&nbsp;
there's one ball, there's three, there's six,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:54.880
there's ten, there's fifteen, and we can continue.&nbsp;
At each stage, what we're doing to go from here to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.880 --> 00:02:03.640
here, say, is we're adding an extra row of balls&nbsp;
at the bottom so that T₃ there is reproduced here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:03.640 --> 00:02:09.360
and then we add four more balls to get&nbsp;
T₄. Similarly, the T₄ is reproduced here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:09.360 --> 00:02:15.800
and we're adding five new balls to get T₅.&nbsp;
Here are the triangular numbers: 1, 3, 6,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:22.600
10, and 15, and so on. It's a little bit&nbsp;
less obvious now what a general formula&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:27.560
for the nth triangular number is, and&nbsp;
that's what we want—something just like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.560 --> 00:02:33.840
this but telling us what exactly that Tₙ&nbsp;
is in terms of n. Triangular numbers have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.840 --> 00:02:39.960
been studied since antiquity, and they&nbsp;
have lots of interesting properties.

00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:45.800
Here is a way of analyzing patterns of numbers&nbsp;
in a more general way which applies also to other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.800 --> 00:02:54.040
interesting sequences or patterns. We write&nbsp;
down the sequence starting, say, with 1, 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:54.040 --> 00:03:01.000
6, 10—these are our triangular numbers—and&nbsp;
then above any two of them we write what the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:06.120
difference is. The difference between 3 and&nbsp;
1 is 2, the difference between 6 and 3 is 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.120 --> 00:03:13.160
and so on. Or to put it another way, we write how&nbsp;
much we have to add to this one to get to the next&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:13.160 --> 00:03:20.240
one, and we've seen already that these differences&nbsp;
increase linearly. They go through all the natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:25.720
numbers. That's made a little bit clearer&nbsp;
by actually deciding to start our triangular&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:30.640
numbers with zero. Then we have a difference&nbsp;
of one as well, which makes it aesthetically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.640 --> 00:03:37.200
a little bit more pleasant. So let's do that.&nbsp;
We could also examine this sequence, which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:41.880
just the sequence of all natural numbers in terms&nbsp;
of differences. Well, the difference between any&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:48.880
two of them is just one, so there's the line&nbsp;
of differences between the natural numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:57.520
and of course, the differences between these are&nbsp;
all zero, and that's sort of where things stop.

00:03:57.520 --> 00:04:03.240
What about a formula for the nth triangular&nbsp;
number? Well, here's T₄, and another way of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:11.080
thinking about what that is is it's 1 + 2 +&nbsp;
3 + 4. So there it is there as a sum. Another&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:19.440
way of representing this triangle of circles is to&nbsp;
represent it more with some boxes: 4, 3, 2, 1. If&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:25.400
we do it that way, then we can play the following&nbsp;
trick. We can take our copy of T₄ over here in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:25.400 --> 00:04:31.960
blue, and then we can take a second copy of it as&nbsp;
well in red, invert it, and put it on top to match&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.960 --> 00:04:39.920
up and form a rectangle. In this case, a rectangle&nbsp;
of sides four and five. That's telling us that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:52.200
2 * T₄ is 4 * 5, and that works in general. 2 * Tₙ&nbsp;
is going to be a rectangle with sides n and n + 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.200 --> 00:05:03.240
so the total area will be n * (n + 1), from which&nbsp;
we deduce that Tₙ is equal to n * (n + 1) / 2. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:03.240 --> 00:05:12.880
here's another use of letters in algebra to allow&nbsp;
us to write formulas for patterns. The n here is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:21.680
not representing an unknown number so much as a&nbsp;
general number, and it's allowing us to express&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.680 --> 00:05:29.480
an arithmetical fact that's valid not just for one&nbsp;
triangular number but for any triangular number.

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:34.040
In fact, this formula is an&nbsp;
important formula because it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:34.040 --> 00:05:39.280
directly connected with this kind of&nbsp;
arithmetic sequence. In other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:48.240
we can interpret that little computation we made&nbsp;
about Tₙ as a formula for this arithmetic series:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:55.480
1 + 2 + 3 + all the way up to n. The sum of&nbsp;
all the numbers from 1 to n, which is just the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:55.480 --> 00:06:05.040
number of balls in the nth triangular number,&nbsp;
is n * (n + 1) / 2. That's our formula for Tₙ.

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:10.880
This kind of formula is sometimes a little bit&nbsp;
ambiguous, and so we mathematicians like to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:18.840
introduce a more precise notation for talking&nbsp;
about sums. This is the summation notation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.840 --> 00:06:26.240
represented by this capital Greek letter Sigma&nbsp;
(Σ) for sum. So here's our convention: instead&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:37.240
of writing 1 + 2 + 3 + 4 + 5, we'll simply write&nbsp;
the sum from k = 1 to 5 of k. So this expression&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:45.720
right here means this by definition. Here's a more&nbsp;
general example: the sum of all the numbers from 1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.720 --> 00:06:53.760
to n, 1 + 2 + 3 + 4 all the way up to n - 1 and up&nbsp;
to n. That sum is now represented in the summation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.760 --> 00:07:04.160
notation by this sign, the sigma. That stands for&nbsp;
sum. This index k is telling us what, first of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:12.520
all, we're summing and what the range of summation&nbsp;
is. k is running from 1 to n, and we're summing k.

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:18.480
The beauty of this summation notation is that it's&nbsp;
quite flexible and allows us to talk about other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:29.320
kinds of sums. For example, 1² + 2² + 3² + 4² +&nbsp;
5² could be written more economically as the sum&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.840 --> 00:07:38.600
k = 1 to 5 of k². Here's the general formula that&nbsp;
extends this. I'll just give it to you for now;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:44.400
we'll have a look at the proof later on.&nbsp;
The sum of all the squares from 1 up to n,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:45.680 --> 00:07:59.200
so the sum k = 1 to n of k² is n * (n + 1) * (2n +&nbsp;
1) / 6. So if n happened to be five, then we would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:07.120
have a five here, a six here, an eleven here,&nbsp;
the sixes would cancel, and we would get 55.

00:08:07.120 --> 00:08:11.920
This last sum that we looked at, the sum&nbsp;
of all the squares, can also be studied in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:11.920 --> 00:08:18.320
terms of a table of differences. It's also quite&nbsp;
interesting. The differences between the squares&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:18.320 --> 00:08:27.760
are all the odd numbers: 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, and so&nbsp;
on. Further differences are all two and then zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:34.880
so that's relatively easy. But we can also&nbsp;
extend this table downwards as long as we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:40.520
have a starting point. So suppose we start with&nbsp;
zero. Then this line is going to be the line of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:47.720
the sums of squares. This 55 here represents 1²&nbsp;
+ 2² + all the way up to 5². That's the number we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.720 --> 00:08:53.560
already calculated. So here are the sums of&nbsp;
squares. That's a more complicated sequence&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:59.200
from the sequence of squares obtained by&nbsp;
going down in this table of differences.

00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:04.560
This is just the beginning of&nbsp;
talking about patterns of numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:04.560 --> 00:09:09.200
and next time we're going to look at some&nbsp;
more patterns to give us some more practice&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:18.040
in trying to understand geometrical patterns&nbsp;
arithmetically and using algebra to encode the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.040 --> 00:09:29.120
results. So I hope you'll join me for that.&nbsp;
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:09:29.120 --> 00:09:30.120
[Music]

